- We compute the length of the LIS using `lengthOfLIS`
- We need to prove that this computed length satisfies the postcond `lengthOfLIS_postcond`

The `lengthOfLIS` function computes the length of the LIS using a standard dynamic programming approach:
- It initializes a dp array where `dp[i]` represents the length of the longest increasing subsequence ending at index `i`
- It iterates over each index `i` and for each previous index `j`, if `nums[j] < nums[i]` and `dp[j] + 1 > dp[i]`, it updates `dp[i]`
- Finally, it returns the maximum value in the dp array

The `lengthOfLIS_postcond` defines what it means for a given length to be the correct length of the LIS:
- It considers all possible non-empty subseqs of `nums`
- It computes their lengths
- It requires that the computed length is both achievable (i.e., there exists an increasing subsequence of that length) and maximal (i.e., no longer increasing subsequence exists)

